1
00:00:00,301 --> 00:00:13,297
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-harto sambha sambodasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:15,699 --> 00:00:19,364
So this evening I've chosen this topic of renunciation.

3
00:00:19,725 --> 00:00:21,626
Now it's not a word we particularly love.

4
00:00:22,608 --> 00:00:26,713
We don't fall for it, you know.

5
00:00:27,553 --> 00:00:33,381
But you won't find a wisdom tradition that doesn't have some level of sensual restraint in its teachings.

6
00:00:33,462 --> 00:00:38,527
I mean, consider, you know, Lent for Christians and Ramadan for Muslims.

7
00:00:39,390 --> 00:00:46,598
And the Hindu tradition and the Jains, of course, all have some form of fasting as part of their practice.

8
00:00:46,618 --> 00:00:49,442
Yeah.

9
00:00:49,463 --> 00:00:53,527
So now in, you know, in the Buddha Dharma, we all

10
00:00:54,200 --> 00:00:58,204
has made this distinction between self-mortification and renunciation.

11
00:00:59,344 --> 00:01:03,808
By self-mortification, we understand that the body is to blame.

12
00:01:04,049 --> 00:01:06,492
So if we lost our tongues, we wouldn't have any greed.

13
00:01:06,512 --> 00:01:12,977
And of course, the body himself went under such practices, nearly starving himself to death.

14
00:01:14,780 --> 00:01:22,046
And he ended up by saying that that sort of practice was just adding more suffering to the already discontent of life.

15
00:01:22,870 --> 00:01:27,016
But renunciation is the restraint of the senses, right?

16
00:01:27,036 --> 00:01:30,921
Understanding that it's nothing to do with the body, but our relationship to it.

17
00:01:33,524 --> 00:01:39,933
So the path of renunciation, there is a direct path through renunciation.

18
00:01:41,174 --> 00:01:46,481
And of course, you know, you'll get monks and nuns who live way out in the jungle.

19
00:01:46,522 --> 00:01:52,810
They're completely renouncing any contact with the sensual life.

20
00:01:53,161 --> 00:01:57,487
and only going into the village to get some alms.

21
00:01:59,751 --> 00:02:06,843
But to understand this, to understand the importance of renunciation, we have to really go back to the roots of the Buddha's teaching.

22
00:02:07,024 --> 00:02:09,829
And that always lies in this delusion of a self.

23
00:02:12,552 --> 00:02:14,316
So what do we mean by that?

24
00:02:14,436 --> 00:02:19,084
Well, whatever you finish this sentence with, I am renunciation.

25
00:02:19,840 --> 00:02:22,563
Whenever you finish that with, that's what you're not.

26
00:02:23,585 --> 00:02:28,551
And that's what we, of course, presume ourselves to be.

27
00:02:29,193 --> 00:02:33,038
In fact, the I in the I am is also part of that delusion.

28
00:02:34,180 --> 00:02:38,806
So it's the problem of this me always wanting to be happy.

29
00:02:39,967 --> 00:02:41,110
Now, that's not so bad.

30
00:02:41,310 --> 00:02:48,479
You know, the Buddha actually has a whole chapter in the Dhammapada devoted to being happy, you know, a happy self.

31
00:02:49,117 --> 00:02:58,188
But it's just what we are seeking for our happiness, which is going to cause disappointment and eventually a bit of sorrow.

32
00:03:01,432 --> 00:03:09,703
So that's easy to overcome when we keep reminding ourselves that everything, absolutely everything arises and passes away and does not repeat.

33
00:03:10,544 --> 00:03:13,948
So you can't repeat the party that you had.

34
00:03:14,468 --> 00:03:16,070
It just doesn't happen.

35
00:03:16,826 --> 00:03:19,570
It's only going to cause suffering trying to do that.

36
00:03:21,513 --> 00:03:36,433
And so when we become dependent on something, the mobile, or a person that we become dependent on, then, you know, when we lose it, that's where the pain is, yeah?

37
00:03:38,437 --> 00:03:40,218
So...

38
00:03:40,925 --> 00:04:07,776
what we have to find out is where does this self manifest and that's the point of desire that's the direct psychological indicator that the self is active but it's a certain type of desire there's a special word in Pali for it this tanha there are other words for desire but this specific desire is the one that leads to indulgence it's the one that leads us to attachment yeah

39
00:04:08,110 --> 00:04:12,477
So it obviously includes all the physical senses, such as food and sex.

40
00:04:12,978 --> 00:04:18,605
But it's the sensual pleasures, too, you know, like art, nature, human association.

41
00:04:19,047 --> 00:04:23,132
All that all comes under the name of sensual.

42
00:04:23,634 --> 00:04:24,074
It's right.

43
00:04:24,435 --> 00:04:26,497
Some people only think of sexual, but it's not.

44
00:04:26,519 --> 00:04:32,026
It's the total sense organ of the psychophysical organism.

45
00:04:32,427 --> 00:04:32,648
Right.

46
00:04:33,228 --> 00:04:34,651
Which includes the intellect.

47
00:04:34,891 --> 00:04:35,232
Yeah.

48
00:04:35,482 --> 00:04:58,653
all the stuff we learn the history science etc um all the stuff we talk about the politics say no more um and and the culture etc it's all the imagination the fantasy all that's part of the sensual life uh and uh and of course the pleasures and joys we get from work yeah

49
00:04:59,122 --> 00:05:09,978
So everything we're doing, everything we experience, we always have to be careful that there is this little bit of tanha when it's making us happy.

50
00:05:10,399 --> 00:05:27,324
And even in the practice, when we enter into beautiful states of mind, a bit of peacefulness, a bit of joy, and those concentration exercises that some of you might practice, the absorptions, you become attached to them, yeah?

51
00:05:28,250 --> 00:05:32,175
So all this would be perfectly lovely except for the clinging.

52
00:05:32,636 --> 00:05:35,500
So that's why we're practicing renunciation, right?

53
00:05:35,521 --> 00:05:39,927
It's a way of letting go of our cravings, no matter how small they are.

54
00:05:41,769 --> 00:05:46,115
So the importance of Nakama is found in the Eightfold Noble Path.

55
00:05:46,216 --> 00:05:53,447
So the first, of course, is right understanding, which is exactly what we're trying to do here.

56
00:05:53,983 --> 00:05:56,927
And the second one is to do with right intentions.

57
00:05:57,028 --> 00:06:08,781
Sometimes it's translated as right thoughts, but intentions, I think, captures it better because it's the intentions that create the attitudes that then manifest in speech, in action and in our livelihoods.

58
00:06:09,422 --> 00:06:12,144
So what are these right intentions?

59
00:06:12,165 --> 00:06:13,947
Well, the first one is renunciation.

60
00:06:15,189 --> 00:06:17,310
The second one is non-ill will.

61
00:06:18,351 --> 00:06:20,514
And the third one is harmlessness.

62
00:06:21,473 --> 00:06:24,076
So how do we put this teaching into practice?

63
00:06:24,637 --> 00:06:26,158
Well, we can start little, you know.

64
00:06:26,177 --> 00:06:28,841
It's getting used to letting go of things.

65
00:06:31,625 --> 00:06:35,067
I mean, those of you who've been on retreats, you know all about this, really.

66
00:06:35,088 --> 00:06:41,274
But it's good just to remind ourselves that we ought to do it as a little daily practice also.

67
00:06:42,877 --> 00:06:51,447
So, for instance, if you find yourself snacking and grazing throughout the day, you know, at a particular time, say TV in the evening, you know,

68
00:06:52,185 --> 00:06:54,790
And you recognize it as unhealthy.

69
00:06:54,970 --> 00:06:55,310
Yeah.

70
00:06:55,329 --> 00:06:56,252
So you make a decision.

71
00:06:56,692 --> 00:06:57,112
Stop it.

72
00:06:57,233 --> 00:06:59,276
I'm going to stop it, you see.

73
00:07:00,557 --> 00:07:03,942
But then you have to remind yourself, you have to bear the discomfort.

74
00:07:05,043 --> 00:07:12,074
So every time the word toast comes to mind, you see, or biscuit, yeah, whatever comes to mind, the alarm bell should go off.

75
00:07:12,093 --> 00:07:12,514
Yeah.

76
00:07:12,535 --> 00:07:17,562
Then we repeat the reasons to ourselves why we're not going to, you know, fall for it.

77
00:07:17,963 --> 00:07:21,266
We're going to renounce it and then reaffirm that determination.

78
00:07:21,608 --> 00:07:21,788
Yeah.

79
00:07:22,932 --> 00:07:30,940
Now, surprisingly, these desires begin to really loosen up after two or three days and they go.

80
00:07:30,980 --> 00:07:34,485
And we regain our agency, right?

81
00:07:34,504 --> 00:07:37,288
We gain back our control over our appetites.

82
00:07:37,408 --> 00:07:38,589
I mean, that's what we're heading for.

83
00:07:39,891 --> 00:07:43,995
You know, because generally speaking, we're enslaved to these things.

84
00:07:44,055 --> 00:07:48,420
And as soon as they come up, they come up as demands and they become as needs.

85
00:07:48,482 --> 00:07:49,783
Well, they're not needs, are they?

86
00:07:50,877 --> 00:08:04,031
But even so, even when we've got through that discomfort and now we feel we've got our agency back, you always have to be careful about that little demon of the self, you know, the demon of desire.

87
00:08:04,452 --> 00:08:05,194
It's only lying low.

88
00:08:05,494 --> 00:08:09,237
If we're not careful, we'll soon become an obedient servant again.

89
00:08:11,300 --> 00:08:19,449
So we have to remind ourselves not until the delusive self has been completely extinguished will such unskillful desires cease.

90
00:08:20,779 --> 00:08:48,238
so now here we might make a little distinction between boredom and disinterest so remember that desires are excited by stimuli and they lose their intensity over time so that's when we get bored with something right and uh taking food for instance as our little object here so it's the same you can't keep eating the same biscuit you've got to look for something else we need variety

91
00:08:48,860 --> 00:08:52,683
But given enough time, however, we go back to our favourite biscuit.

92
00:08:52,744 --> 00:08:54,085
See, that's how boredom works.

93
00:08:54,164 --> 00:08:55,446
It gets fed up with something.

94
00:08:55,846 --> 00:09:00,892
We seek something else and then we remember, oh, wait a minute, what about my favourite biscuit?

95
00:09:01,032 --> 00:09:03,354
And then you're back to that.

96
00:09:04,475 --> 00:09:06,417
Disinterest is something different.

97
00:09:06,437 --> 00:09:07,977
It's a spiritual quality.

98
00:09:08,359 --> 00:09:09,580
It is exactly that.

99
00:09:09,659 --> 00:09:11,562
We lose interest in something.

100
00:09:12,101 --> 00:09:17,368
So we don't longer care about biscuits or what biscuits we have or even if there are any.

101
00:09:17,648 --> 00:09:17,888
Yeah.

102
00:09:18,525 --> 00:09:21,609
Yet there's still the enjoyment of biscuit if it comes our way.

103
00:09:22,429 --> 00:09:29,957
So to quote an ancient Zen master, when asked to explain Buddha Dharma, his reply was, no preference.

104
00:09:31,659 --> 00:09:33,402
No preference.

105
00:09:33,422 --> 00:09:34,703
That's where we're aiming, right?

106
00:09:34,764 --> 00:09:37,687
We're aiming to a point where we're not sticking onto anything.

107
00:09:39,269 --> 00:09:42,491
At a mental level, it's views and opinions, you know.

108
00:09:42,943 --> 00:09:46,812
It's the same sort of attitude that we apply, sort of renouncing this.

109
00:09:47,113 --> 00:09:52,404
I'm right and everybody else is wrong or almost wrong or not as not as right as I am.

110
00:09:52,445 --> 00:09:57,417
See, so there's always a conceit that underlies these positions.

111
00:09:57,657 --> 00:10:02,488
See, doesn't matter what it is, religious, political, cultural and so on.

112
00:10:04,087 --> 00:10:08,014
Now, it doesn't mean to say that we have to change our understanding.

113
00:10:08,134 --> 00:10:08,695
It may be.

114
00:10:08,855 --> 00:10:09,615
It may be fine.

115
00:10:10,015 --> 00:10:14,503
But being open to others, allowing us to nuance our understanding, yeah?

116
00:10:14,523 --> 00:10:20,150
And occasionally, we might even change our opinion, especially today with all this polarization.

117
00:10:23,355 --> 00:10:28,802
And then there's the members of the human community, aware of climate crisis, of mindless consumption.

118
00:10:29,403 --> 00:10:33,690
So we have a duty here to simplify our lifestyle, yeah?

119
00:10:34,666 --> 00:10:36,928
How many pairs of shoes do we actually need?

120
00:10:37,328 --> 00:10:40,592
When you're buying some clothing, do you actually need it?

121
00:10:41,974 --> 00:10:45,317
And then we have to see that the culture is caught up.

122
00:10:45,597 --> 00:10:52,446
We are caught up in this selfishness that's been generated by neoliberalism and consumerism.

123
00:10:53,447 --> 00:10:56,090
And then we get the idea of giving something away.

124
00:10:56,110 --> 00:11:03,238
In the very act of generosity, we're actually exercising renunciation.

125
00:11:04,702 --> 00:11:08,207
And of course, it makes living a little lighter.

126
00:11:09,970 --> 00:11:13,715
When it comes to personal relationships, you see, we possess other people.

127
00:11:14,355 --> 00:11:15,918
So it manifests as control.

128
00:11:15,977 --> 00:11:16,739
We manipulate.

129
00:11:16,820 --> 00:11:20,183
We use anger, threats of abandonment, spiteful action.

130
00:11:20,684 --> 00:11:22,547
Yeah, we hold grudges and nurse them.

131
00:11:23,087 --> 00:11:25,812
We offer presents and promises to entice them.

132
00:11:26,873 --> 00:11:31,740
And becoming aware of those little behaviors, you know, developing the skills of forgiveness, trust.

133
00:11:32,210 --> 00:11:35,700
training ourselves to see the situation from the other person's point of view.

134
00:11:36,261 --> 00:11:38,769
All that is the exercise of renunciation.

135
00:11:40,214 --> 00:11:40,995
Then there's the news.

136
00:11:41,236 --> 00:11:42,139
Oh my goodness, yeah.

137
00:11:44,365 --> 00:11:44,667
You know,

138
00:11:44,883 --> 00:11:58,798
trailing through the news every morning, every evening, during the day, you know, always onto it, finding out what's happened next with this constant daily messaging of war, Trumpian shocks, injustice, and so on.

139
00:11:59,299 --> 00:12:04,405
So it's no wonder that we can build up a sense of hopelessness, disempowerment.

140
00:12:06,908 --> 00:12:14,518
Now we can undermine this by method, of course, but sometimes the best policy is just to stop listening, you know, to limit the input.

141
00:12:15,629 --> 00:12:21,402
During my first 12 years as a monastic, I took very little interest in world affairs.

142
00:12:21,701 --> 00:12:23,706
You know, for long times, I was quite secluded.

143
00:12:25,330 --> 00:12:33,347
And it took a while when I came, when I got back into ordinary daily life here to find out what was happening.

144
00:12:33,467 --> 00:12:35,292
But I never felt I'd lost anything.

145
00:12:37,515 --> 00:12:44,644
The Buddha, in the discourse on developing metta, which we read at the end, again, advises us not to be too busy.

146
00:12:44,725 --> 00:12:47,208
So again, it's about decluttering our lives.

147
00:12:48,669 --> 00:12:50,192
How are we spending our time?

148
00:12:50,893 --> 00:12:52,235
What are we spending it on?

149
00:12:52,514 --> 00:13:00,326
Social media, doing things, always having to do something, you know, trying to get back to just being every so often.

150
00:13:00,346 --> 00:13:03,809
Being and doing.

151
00:13:04,650 --> 00:13:10,740
Do we find ourselves in a sense of rush, of anxiety, even a sense of occasional overwhelm?

152
00:13:10,860 --> 00:13:12,744
See, then you have to prioritize, right?

153
00:13:12,764 --> 00:13:15,788
You have to let go, let go of some engagements.

154
00:13:15,808 --> 00:13:28,330
And of course, when we do that, we find ourselves being more relaxed and we meditate better and become more aware about this underlying turbulence in our hearts, which is often fueling the overactivity.

155
00:13:29,980 --> 00:13:34,749
So it's allowing that to exhaust itself and bring a sort of greater sense of calmness.

156
00:13:35,450 --> 00:13:45,269
And it really is a wise thing to constantly remind ourselves that tranquility, calmness, tranquility is a factor of enlightenment.

157
00:13:46,471 --> 00:13:47,854
A factor of awakening.

158
00:13:49,657 --> 00:13:52,822
Now, renunciation isn't the fullness of the spiritual life.

159
00:13:52,922 --> 00:13:56,346
I mean, such practice, you know, brings a sense of ease into our lives.

160
00:13:57,008 --> 00:13:59,572
And it brings with it clean energy.

161
00:13:59,971 --> 00:14:00,192
Yeah.

162
00:14:00,933 --> 00:14:05,581
Letting go of the demands of egoistic self is a relief.

163
00:14:05,941 --> 00:14:07,123
It's not a deprivation.

164
00:14:08,004 --> 00:14:11,509
The energy, the freedom we feel seeks a different focus.

165
00:14:11,889 --> 00:14:12,951
And the focus is the other.

166
00:14:13,111 --> 00:14:13,513
Yeah.

167
00:14:13,533 --> 00:14:14,614
So we're social animals.

168
00:14:14,673 --> 00:14:15,416
Everybody knows that.

169
00:14:15,515 --> 00:14:16,197
We love people.

170
00:14:16,256 --> 00:14:17,097
We love animals.

171
00:14:17,618 --> 00:14:18,700
And we love to help others.

172
00:14:18,980 --> 00:14:23,148
Some of our greatest joys is supporting others in their griefs, in their joys.

173
00:14:24,571 --> 00:14:32,525
But you have to always remember this little devil of self may sneak in and we find ourselves doing good in order to feel happy.

174
00:14:32,546 --> 00:14:35,991
That's no good, you see, right?

175
00:14:36,011 --> 00:14:39,238
Danger lurks in the most heartfelt generosity.

176
00:14:40,804 --> 00:14:47,173
Luckily, it's enough just to acknowledge the skillful motivations and then to reaffirm the good intentions.

177
00:14:47,193 --> 00:14:48,916
So we don't have to be hard on ourselves.

178
00:14:49,557 --> 00:14:51,820
You know, a dash of humility is needed here.

179
00:14:52,301 --> 00:14:55,524
Just acknowledge that the work on ourselves is yet to be done.

180
00:14:56,306 --> 00:14:59,029
That's a comfort.

181
00:14:59,049 --> 00:15:04,878
The Buddha warns us, you know, the path is gradual, very gradual in my experience anyway.

182
00:15:06,220 --> 00:15:07,841
So, renunciations.

183
00:15:09,255 --> 00:15:10,278
Well, it's important.

184
00:15:10,317 --> 00:15:20,095
We need to reflect on our lives, see where we're sticking onto something, someone, some behavior, and just allow ourselves to let go for a while.

185
00:15:20,275 --> 00:15:28,230
See, suffering gladly the pain of releasing the numbed cramp and enjoy a bit of peace.

186
00:15:31,897 --> 00:15:32,697
I can only hope.

187
00:15:33,623 --> 00:15:45,337
My words have been of some assistance that I have not caused confusion and that by your practice of renunciation you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

